<p:sld xmlns:a="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/drawingml/2006/main" xmlns:r="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/officeDocument/2006/relationships" xmlns:p="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/presentationml/2006/main"><p:cSld><p:spTree><p:nvGrpSpPr><p:cNvPr id="1" name=""/><p:cNvGrpSpPr/><p:nvPr/></p:nvGrpSpPr><p:grpSpPr><a:xfrm><a:off x="0" y="0"/><a:ext cx="0" cy="0"/><a:chOff x="0" y="0"/><a:chExt cx="0" cy="0"/></a:xfrm></p:grpSpPr><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="2" name="Title 1"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{FF529B09-7F05-212A-90B1-9825CB7942AD}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph type="title"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Go simpler</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp><p:sp><p:nvSpPr><p:cNvPr id="3" name="Content Placeholder 2"><a:extLst><a:ext uri="{FF2B5EF4-FFF2-40B4-BE49-F238E27FC236}"><a16:creationId xmlns:a16="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/drawing/2014/main" id="{6147F963-D61B-501B-55F9-0098AFC5C605}"/></a:ext></a:extLst></p:cNvPr><p:cNvSpPr><a:spLocks noGrp="1"/></p:cNvSpPr><p:nvPr><p:ph idx="1"/></p:nvPr></p:nvSpPr><p:spPr/><p:txBody><a:bodyPr/><a:lstStyle/><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Even if you explain it slowly and sequentially, some concepts may just be too difficult for your audience to quickly understand. </a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"><a:solidFill><a:srgbClr val="0E9ED5"/></a:solidFill></a:rPr><a:t>Learning how to abstract away irrelevant information to provide an explanation at just the right level of detail </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>for your target audience is an important skill to hone, especially for data scientists who tend to dive deep into technical concepts too quickly. </a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>One good way to do this is to </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" b="1" dirty="0"><a:solidFill><a:srgbClr val="0E9ED5"/></a:solidFill></a:rPr><a:t>use analogies </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>that capture the essence of the concept you need to communicate without any jargon.</a:t></a:r></a:p><a:p><a:pPr lvl="1"/><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t>Example: To explain what is an API to non-technical audiences, you can use the analogy of a restaurant! The menu is the documentation, the waiter is the API server, and the kitchen is the backend service. You can only order specific items from the menu, with some </a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0" err="1"/><a:t>customisations</a:t></a:r><a:r><a:rPr lang="en-US" dirty="0"/><a:t> (like parameters that you pass to the API!)</a:t></a:r></a:p></p:txBody></p:sp></p:spTree><p:extLst><p:ext uri="{BB962C8B-B14F-4D97-AF65-F5344CB8AC3E}"><p14:creationId xmlns:p14="http://schemas.microsoft.com/office/powerpoint/2010/main" val="1380072150"/></p:ext></p:extLst></p:cSld><p:clrMapOvr><a:masterClrMapping/></p:clrMapOvr></p:sld>